Generally, the possible explanation can be divided into static and dynamic detection mechanism [81,82], which can be distinguished by their different dependences on the temperature and excited-state lifetime. The fluorescence lifetime is an important parameter in judging the mechanism of fluorescence quenching mechanism, which can often reflect whether the quenching effect is based on a static or a dynamic mechanism [83]. The photo-luminescent decay curves of two different analysts (one is the CDs@Eu(D-Cam) suspensions, the other is the CDs@Eu(D-Cam) sample suspensions with the addition of 170 μM L-Phe) were both explored (Fig. 7
                        ). As listed in Table 2
                        , the fluorescence lifetime of the CDs@Eu(D-Cam) was 1.763755 ns. The photo-luminescent lifetime of the Eu(D-Cam) with the addition of 170 μM L-Phe was 4.404288 ns, which is significantly larger than that of CDs@Eu(D-Cam). When L-Phe is added, luminescence lifetimes of CDs@Eu(D-Cam) gradually decrease, indicating the existence of dynamic quenching mechanism. Similar phenomena can be observed in the recently reported lanthanide chemosensor [La(TPT)(DMSO)2]·H2O (H3TPT = p-terphenyl-3,4″,5- tricarboxylic acid) [84], such dynamic quenching mechanism can be governed by the diffusive collisions between the electron-deficient Fe3+ and the terphenyl moieties of H4L. The result also indicate the detection object L-Phe should has some specific interactions with CDs@Eu(D-Cam) sample, which further induce the increase of fluorescence lifetime, therefore the detection process may be ascribed to dynamic mechanism, namely the existence of diffusive collisions between the L-Phe and CDs@Eu(D-Cam).
